<br>
To Tom and Joe, and to doc spatz who is probably foaming at the mouth.<br><br>
Tom I received your e-mail messageg today and have responded here and will response via e-mail. Thank you.<br><br>
Joe, I  want to thank you for your response and appreciate the thoughts you shared here as they reveal that you have given it much thought and serious consideration and have presented for us a well thought out presentation.<br><br>
I agree with you whole heartily with the lone exception. <br><br>
If  I feel any guilt or remorse today, it is because I feel that not only was it A JUST WAR, but that I could have done more.<br><br>
More for the Vietnamese farmer that believed in us and desired to have the same freedom we so freely enjoyed.<br><br>
More for the American fighting men who did not receive the honor and glory due him for having accomplished WITH HONOR the duties and responsibilities their country called upon them to do. <br><br>
I believe that PTSD to a certain degree does happen to all those who have participated in battle. <br><br>
Following a fierce battle on May 30, 1968 when a truck convoy was massacred by an entrenched enemy force it was the arm of a fellow Marine that awoke me from &quot;THAT PROTECTIVE SHIELD OF DISASSOCAITION OF THE SORROWS OF WAR,&quot; that allowed me to wreak havoc upon an enemy's machine guns position so others could survive. The battle had long been over, but in my mind I was still firing. It was not until the marine lifted up my guns cover that I realized that my guns barrel was melted, and that I had fired all of our guns ammo. With wounded and dead Marines on both sides of me, it was not until the Marine spoke that I released the trigger. <br><br>
However, I believe much of PTSD was caused by the dishonor wreaked against those that did do their country's battle. Who were never allowed to share their moments of glory and honor, pains and sorrows with their loved ones. Indeed, I believe many such hero's till this day remained pinned down in those rice paddies of history's shame because as Joe mentioned above. <br>
&quot;Somehow, the crimes of a careless and distorted few are projected by some as the actions of all Vietnam vets. This is a falsehood that needs to be corrected.  <br><br>
A former Marine lieutenant in our unit once said.<br>
&quot; The downfall was in the lack of resolve at home to support our troops. The morale busters were the Jane Fondas, the draft dodgers, congressional rule-makers, and most of all and the worst of all, the silent majority.&quot;<br><br>
The silent American that did not care enough to become involved, I believe contributed much to the woes of PTSD. <br>
Today, I believe that it's time for us to disassociate ourselves from histories shame, its time to embrace the honor due those that fought a just war. To realize that THE LAST AMERICAN WAR FOUGHT WITH REAL HONOR was accomplished in the rice paddie fields of South East Asia and we were there.  <br>
As I've said before,<br><br>
&quot;We will never see battles again as we did in Viet Nam. If we failed, it was not because we did not do our duty, it was because others entrusted with higher responsibilities failed to do theirs.&quot;<br><br>

